42 (h) One member who is an emergency medical services provider licensed under ORS 682.216; and
43 (i) One member who represents a patient equity organization or is an academic professional
44 specializing in health equity.
45 (2)(a) The committee shall provide advice and recommendations to the board regarding systems
[6]

HB 4053
1 of care related to time-sensitive medical emergencies, including at least cardiac, stroke, airway,
2 sepsis and trauma emergencies. The [commission] committee shall also consider other time-sensitive
3 emergencies including but not limited to sepsis, infectious diseases, pandemics, active seizures and
4 severe respiratory emergencies.
5 (b) The committee shall provide recommendations to the board on:
6 (A) The regionalization and improvement of care for time-sensitive medical emergencies.
7 (B) The designation, using nationally recognized classifications where possible, of emergency
8 medical services centers for the provision of care for time-sensitive medical emergencies. If no na-
9 tionally recognized classifications exist, the committee shall undertake a public deliberation process
10 to establish classifications and submit the established classifications to the board for approval. In
11 establishing and approving classifications, the committee and the board shall prioritize patient care.
12 (3) The committee shall:
13 (a) Advise the board with respect to the board’s duties related to care for cardiac, stroke,
14 trauma and other identified time-sensitive emergencies;
15 (b) Advise the board on potential rules that the board may recommend to the authority for
16 adoption related to care for cardiac, stroke, trauma and other identified time-sensitive emergencies;
17 (c) Analyze data related to care for cardiac, stroke, trauma and other identified time-sensitive
18 emergencies;
19 (d) Recommend to the board improvements to the Emergency Medical Services Program re-
20 garding care for cardiac, stroke, trauma and other identified time-sensitive emergencies; and
21 (e) Identify inequities in the provision of care and provide recommendations to the board and
22 program to resolve the identified inequities.
23 (4) The members of the committee who are physicians must be physicians licensed under ORS
24 chapter 677.
25 (5) The authority may adopt rules as necessary to carry out this section, including rules to adopt
26 the nationally recognized classifications described in subsection (2) of this section.
